      <div xml:id="NA157-kiḷavi">
        <p type="edition">itu poruḷvayiṉ pirinta talaivaṉ paruvam uṇarnta neñciṟku uraittatu.</p>
        <p type="translation" xml:lang="en">This what HE who had separated for the sake of wealth said to [his] heart that had perceived the season.</p>
      </div>
      <div xml:id="NA157">
        <lg type="edition">
<l>            iruṅkaṇ ñālat tīṇṭutoḻi lutavip</l>
<l>            perumpeyal poḻinta vaḻinā ḷamaiyattup</l>
<l>            palpoṟi yaraviṉ celpuṟaṅ kaṭuppa</l>
<l>            yāṟṟaṟa ṉuṇaṅkiya nāṭpata vēṉi</l>
<l>            liṇartutai māatta puṇarkuyil viḷittoṟu </l>
<l>            namvayi ṉiṉaiyu neñcamoṭu kaimmikak</l>
<l>            kēṭṭoṟuṅ kaliḻumāṟ peritē kāṭṭa</l>
<l>            kuṟumpoṟai yayala neṭuntāḷ vēṅkai</l>
<l>            yampūn tātuk kaṉṉa</l>
<l>            nuṇpaḵ ṟitti māa yōḷē.</l>
            </lg>
       <lg type="translation" xml:lang="en">
<l>At the time of successive days when great raining has flown,</l>
<l rend="indent2">having contributed [its] labour here for the world of vast area,</l>
<l>in summer, right on the day(?)<note place="foot">How to understand <term xml:lang="ta">nāḷ patam vēṉil</term>?</note> the water in the river has thinned,</l>
<l rend="indent2">resembling the moving back of the many-spotted snake,</l>
<l rend="indent">whenever the Koels call, uniting in the mango-tree dense with clusters,</l>
<l rend="indent">whenever she hears [it]</l>
<l rend="indent4">she will weep greatly indeed,</l>
<l rend="indent3">exceedingly [vexed](?)<note place="foot">The <term xml:lang="ta">kaimmika</term> seems to be oddly incomplete. For an adverb to <term xml:lang="ta">kaliḻum</term> it is too far off, and anyway there is already <term xml:lang="ta">peritu</term>. Can it be associated here already with the <term xml:lang="ta">kiḷavi</term> idiom where it would go along with <term xml:lang="ta">kaḻipaṭar</term>?</note>, with a heart thinking of us,</l>
<l>– the dark one with fine many beauty spots,</l>
<l rend="indent">as if the pollen of pretty flowers had been shed</l>
<l rend="indent2">from the long-trunked Vēṅkai trees near the short forest height</l>
<l rend="indent3">of the wilderness.</l>
        </lg>
